body:
The module `New-ModuleManifest` doesn't allow the user to produce a file without any comments in it. This offers some limitations in term of CI integration scenarios where you would want to produce the manifest automatically (without it having extra options commented out) and also forces users who don't want those comments in their manifests to manually delete them after the creation.

A simple switch in the `New-ModuleManifest` called `NoComments` to create a file without those comments would give the users more flexibility in terms of using the `New-ModuleManifest`. 

An example of the command:
````
$settings = @{
 Path = ".\manifest.psd1";
 RootModule = ".\module.dll";
}
New-ModuleManifest @settings -NoComments
````

Currently you can pass in a variable to a remote session using the following syntax

$using:variableName

```powershell
param (
    [pscredential]$cred
)
$path = 'd:\repos'
Invoke-Command -CN server123 -ScriptBlock {

    Invoke-Command -CN server456 -Cred $Using:cred -ArgumentList @($using:Path) -ScriptBlock {
        Get-ChildItem -Path $args[0]
    }

}
```

However once you go into the nested session, you have to fall back to using the -ArgumentList array to get to a third hop.

Then also in the nested remote scriptblock, fall back to referencing the input via the $Args array.

Ideally it would be nice if the $using was supported as below.

```powershell
param (
    [pscredential]$cred
)
$path = 'd:\repos'
Invoke-Command -CN server123 -ScriptBlock {

    $nestedpath = $using:path
    Invoke-Command -CN server456 -Cred $Using:cred -ScriptBlock {
        Get-ChildItem -Path $using:nestedpath
    }

}
```

I cannot see too much of an advantage of making up a new nested Scope Using format/syntax to directly access a variable two (2) levels up directly without re-assigning it in the middle scope E.g. $using:2:path   However I think it would be nice if $using:var did work.
